08/02/2005
SKOPJE, Macedonia -- Prosecutors from the UN war crimes tribunal started hearing testimony Monday (7 February) stemming from the so-called Ljuboten case, involving the killing of several ethnic Albanian civilians in a police operation during the 2001 conflict. 
The first official interviewed was Zlatko Keskoski, who headed security for the late President Boris Trajkovski. 
Keskoski is one of four new witnesses subpoenaed to testify about former Interior Minister Ljube Boskovski's possible role in the killings.
In other news Monday, Macedonian Prime Minister Vlado Buckovski called on the parliamentary parties to meet on Wednesday to agree on a joint strategy for EU integration preparations. 
Skopje will present its answers to an EU questionnaire next week. 
(Dnevnik - 08/02/05; A1 TV - 07/02/05)
